Introduction¶

This is an machine learning project classifying the quality of red wine as 'good' or 'bad'. The data is from UC Irvine's Machine Learning Repository.

The data involves wine that are red variants of the Portuguese "Vinho Verde" wine is a unique product from the Minho region of Portugal. Vinho Verde wine typically has medium alcohol content and it particularly appreciatd due to its freshness. You can learn more about Vinho Verde wine by clicking here Viho verde contains more normal wines than excellent or poor ones.

You can view the github repository here.

Data Exploration¶

Input Variables (based on physicochemical tests):¶

  • fixed_acidity: most acids involved with wine or fixed or nonvolatile (do not evaporate readily)
    • Measured: tartaric acid - g / dm^3
  • volatile_acidity: the amount of acetic acid in wine, which at too high of levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste
    • Measured: acetic acid - g / dm^3
  • citric_acid: found in small quantities, citric acid can add 'freshness' and flavor to wines (g)
    • Measured: g / dm^3
  • residual_sugar: the amount of sugar remaining after fermentation stops, it's rare to find wines with less than 1 gram/liter and wines with greater than 45 grams/liter are considered sweet
    • Measured: g / dm^3
  • chlorides: the amount of salt in the wine
    • Measured: sodium chloride - g / dm^3
  • free_sulfur_dioxide: the free form of SO2 exists in equilibrium between molecular SO2 (as a dissolved gas) and bisulfite ion; it prevents microbial growth and the oxidation of wine
    • Measured: mg / dm^3
  • total_sulfur_dioxide: amount of free and bound forms of S02; in low concentrations, SO2 is mostly undetectable in wine, but at free SO2 concentrations over 50 ppm, SO2 becomes evident in the nose and taste of wine
    • Measured: mg / dm^3
  • density: the density of water is close to that of water depending on the percent alcohol and sugar content
    • Measured: g / cm^3
  • pH: describes how acidic or basic a wine is on a scale from 0 (very acidic) to 14 (very basic); most wines are between 3-4 on the pH scale
    • Measured: pH scale
  • sulphates: a wine additive which can contribute to sulfur dioxide gas (S02) levels, wich acts as an antimicrobial and antioxidant
    • Measured: potassium sulphate - g / dm3
  • alcohol: the percent alcohol content of the wine
    • Measured: % by volume

Output Variable (based on sensory data):¶

  • quality: based on sensory data
    • Measured: score between 0 and 10

All of these features seem important in determining the quality of wine.

Distribution¶

Based on the pairplot, it looks like all, but pH and density have distribution that is skewed right. Density and pH have a fairly normal distribution.

Correlation¶

Features with a strong positive correlation(around +0.70):

  • fixed_acidity and citric_acid
  • fixed_acidity and density
  • free_sulfur_dioxide and total_sulfur_dioxide

Features with a strong negative correlation(around -0.70):

  • fixed_acidity and pH

Features with a moderate positive correlation(around +0.50):

  • alcohol and quality

Features with a moderate negative correlation(around -0.50):

  • citric_acid and volatile_acidity
  • pH and citric acid
  • density and alcohol

Features with a weak positive correlation(around +0.30):

  • citric_acid and density
  • citric_acid and sulphates

Features with a weak negative correlation(around -0.30):

  • volatile_acidity and quality
  • density and pH

Some of these relationships make sense like free_sulfur_dioxide and total_sulfur_dioxide and any relationship involving pH and acids (citric_acid, fixed_acidity). I do think it is interesting that volatile_acidity and pH have a weak relatioinship. However, I think two important relationships to highlight is the ones involving quality: alcohol and quality and volatile_acidity and quality. While volatile_acidity and quality has a weak relationship, it is still notable enough to keep in mind when I build my models.

Data Preprocessing¶

I will try my best at feature engineering in order to help improve my models' performance when the time comes.

Quality¶

Going forward, I want to categorize the quality of wine as 'good' and 'bad' instead of keeping it on a scale of 1-10. I feel it is reasonable to deem wine with a score of 7 or higher as 'good' and consider wine with a score less than 7 as 'bad'. By doing so, I will be able to make this more suited for a binary classifier.

In [8]:
rw_data['quality'] = rw_data['quality'].mask(rw_data['quality'] < 7, 0)
rw_data['quality'] = rw_data['quality'].mask(rw_data['quality'] >= 7, 1)

Fixed Acidity¶

After spending some time researching fixed acidity, I don't think there is a proper way of categorizing it based on the properties of fixed acidity. Due to it's wide range, I think I will use decile binning.

Source

In [9]:
# Function: Plot Histogram
def plot_hist(data, alpha, title, xlabel, ylabel) :
   bins = np.linspace(math.ceil(min(data)),
                   math.floor(max(data)),
                   20)
   plt.hist(data, bins=bins, alpha=alpha, edgecolor='black')

   plt.title(title)
   plt.xlabel(xlabel)
   plt.ylabel(ylabel)

   plt.show()
    
plot_hist(rw_data['fixed_acidity'], 0.5, 'Fixed Acidity Distribution', 'Fixed Acidity', 'Count')

Residual Sugar¶

Residual sugar refers to the amount of sugar remaining after fermentation stops. The amount of sugar is what classifies alcohol as "dry" or "sweet" as we see with other alcoholic drinks such as cider or sake. Because of this, we want to classify the wine based on the amount of sugar using this chart:

Free Sulfur Dioxide¶

The level of free sulfur dioxide required to protect wine are pH-dependent. Free sulfur dioxide and pH are positively correlated: as pH goes up, there needs to be higher levels of free sulfur dioxide to protect the wine. A general rule seems to be: You need 50 ppm of Free Sulfur Dioxide with a pH level of 3.6 for adequate protection purposes. From there, +/- 10 ppm for every +/- 0.1 pH level respectively. To bin this, I will divide the feature into 2: those that follow the rule and those that do not.

Source

Total Sulfur Dioxide¶

Due to the strong relationship of "free_sulfur_dioxide and total_sulfur_dioxide", I feel categorizing this feature based off free_sulfur_dioxide seems reasonable. Basically, any free_sulfur_dioxide with 1 will have a total_sulfur_dioxide of 1 and the same goes for 0.

In [19]:
rw_data['total_sulfur_dioxide'] = rw_data['total_sulfur_dioxide'].mask(rw_data['free_sulfur_dioxide'] == 0, 0)
rw_data['total_sulfur_dioxide'] = rw_data['total_sulfur_dioxide'].mask(rw_data['free_sulfur_dioxide'] == 1, 1)

Alcohol¶

On average, wine has an ABV of around 12-15%. I will divide this feature based on the infographic below (except High Alcohol (>15%) because looking at the distribution, there is no wine with alcohol content above 15 present):

  • Low Alcohol: <10%
  • Medium-Low Alcohol: 10-11.5%
  • Medium Alcohol: 11.5-13.5%
  • Medium-High Alcohol: 13.5-15%

Building Machine Learning Models¶

Splitting Data¶

In [27]:
# Prediction Target
Y = rw_data["quality"]

# Predictors
X = rw_data.drop("quality", axis=1)

# Split into training and validation data sets
X_train, X_val, Y_train, Y_val = train_test_split(X, Y, random_state=0)

Testing and Cross Validation¶

To test each of the machine learning models, I will be using cross-validation. Cross-validation is an extension beyond the normal Train-Test split. By running the process on different subsets of the data, the average of the multiple measures of model quality gives a more accurate measure. Luckily, the data set only contains 1,159 examples. If it was bigger (ex 10,000 or more), I would not execute cross-validation due to the time needed to do so for each model. I will execute the normal Train-Test split on the best scoring model. As a friend named "Google" once told me: "cross-validation's purpose is for model checking, not model building."

I will be using the following machine learning models:

  • Gaussian Naive Bayes (NB)
  • Logistic Regression (LR)
  • Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA)
  • Support Vector Machines (SVM)
  • K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)
  • Decision Tree (DT)
  • Random Forest (RF)

I think this is a good mixture of simple linear (LR, LDA) and nonlinear (NB, SVM, KNN, DT, RF) algorithms.

Best Model: Random Forest¶

Random Forest is a supervised learning algorithm which is essentially a mixture of a bunch of Decision Trees or a "Forest of Decision Trees" if you will. Random forest builds multiple decision trees and merges them together to get a more accurate and stable prediction. This algorithm brings extra randomness into model due to the multiple trees. Instead of searching for the best feature while splitting a node, it searches for the best feature among a random subset of features. You can even make trees more random, by using random thresholds on top of it for each feature rather than searching for the best possible thresholds like a normal decision tree does. Random Forest can be tuned and optimized to yield a more accurate score.

In [36]:
# Random Forest
rand_forest = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100)
rand_forest.fit(X_train, Y_train)
Y_pred = rand_forest.predict(X_val)
acc_rand_forest = accuracy_score(Y_val, Y_pred) * 100
print("Random Forest Accuracy Score: ", round(acc_rand_forest, 2,), "%")

Random Forest Accuracy Score:  90.0 %

By executing a normal validation test, we can see that Random Forest yields an accuracy score of 90.0%! This is very high, but let's see if we can make it more accurate.

Feature Importance¶

One great quality of Random Forest is Importance Feature which helps see which features are relatively more important. We can use this quality to drop the less important features to give a better accuracy score. The general rule of thumb is that the more features you have, the more likely the model will suffer from overfitting.

In [37]:
importance = pd.DataFrame({'feature':X_train.columns,'importance':np.round(rand_forest.feature_importances_,3)})

Hyperparameter Tuning¶

Another nice quality of Random Forest is Hyperparameter Tuning. This is the ability to adjust the parameters in order to optimize the performance of the algorithm. Some parameters are made during training, but hyperparameters can be adjusted before training. I will be tuning the following parameters:

  • criterion: measure of the quality of the split: gini(indicator of how messy the data is) or entropy(measure of misclassification)
  • max_features: max number of features considered for splitting a node
  • n_estimators: number of trees in the foreset
  • max_depth: max number of levels in each decision tree
  • min_samples_leaf: min number of data points placed in a node before the node is split
  • min_samples_split: min number of data points allowed in a leaf node

I will use GridSearchCV() to evaluate which are the best hyperparameters to use.

In [42]:

Evaluation¶

Now that I have a more properly tuned model, I can start evaluating its performance even further using Confusion Matrix, Classification Report, and ROC AUC Curve. which are typically used to evaluate the algorithm's prediction results.

Confusion Matrix¶

Confusion Matrix presents an accuracy of the model showing True Positive, True Negative, False Positive, and False Negative.

In [45]:
confusion_matrix(Y_val, Y_pred)
Out[45]:
array([[330,  25],
       [ 16,  29]], dtype=int64)

The first row shows bad quality wine predictions:

  • True Negative: 330 wines were correctly classified as bad
  • False Positive: 25 wines were wrongly classified as bad (Type I Error)

The second row shows good quality wine predictions:

  • False Negative: 16 wines were wrongly classified as good (Type II Error)
  • True Positive: 29 wines were correctly classified as good

Classification Report (Precision, Recall, F1 Score)¶

Classification Report displays the precision, recall, f1-score, and support for each class. It gives a quick idea of accuracy using number of errors. (Reminder: 0 = bad quality 1 = good quality wine)

  • Precision: how often it correctly Predicted Good
  • Recall: how often Actual Good = Predicted Good
  • F1-score: weighted average of Precision and Recall (depends on Precision and Recall scores)
  • Support: number of samples for both that exist
In [46]:
class_report = classification_report(Y_val, Y_pred)
print(class_report)

             precision    recall  f1-score   support

          0       0.95      0.93      0.94       355
          1       0.54      0.64      0.59        45

avg / total       0.91      0.90      0.90       400

The model correctly classified 95% as bad (Precision) with a Recall score of 93%. With high Precision and Recall score, it is no surprise the F1-score is 94%. The model correctly classified 54% as good (Precision) with a Recall score of 64%. With a moderate Precision and Recall score, it is no surprise the F1-score is 59%.

Overall, the model did a better job of classifying bad quality wines than it did for good quality wines. However, I believe this is so due to the fact that there were only 45 examples of good quality wines while there are 355 examples of bad quality wines. However, this is also due to the fact that there were more "normal" wines included in this data set as mentioned earlier which included a lot more 5s and 6s than any other score. Since, I classified "good" as 7 or higher, this means there were less examples of good quality wine included in the data set.

ROC AUC Curve¶

Another way to evaluate and compare this binary classifier is the ROC AUC Curve. This curve plots the true positive rate (Recall) against the false positive rate. In the plot, the red line in the middle represents a purely random classifier meaning the blue curve (my classifier) should be as far away from the red line as possible.

In [47]:
# Getting the probabilities of our predictions
y_scores = rand_forest.predict_proba(X_train)
y_scores = y_scores[:,1]

# Calculate False Positive and True Positive
false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate, thresholds = roc_curve(Y_train, y_scores)

# Function: Plotting False Positive against True Positive
def plot_roc_curve(false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate, label=None) :
    plt.plot(false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate, linewidth=2, label=label)
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'r', linewidth=4)
    plt.axis([0, 1, 0, 1])
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate (FPR)', fontsize=16)
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate (TPR)', fontsize=16)

plt.figure(figsize=(14, 7))
plot_roc_curve(false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate)
plt.show()

As we can barely see the blue line, it means the model did a really good job.

ROC AUC Score¶

The ROC AUC Score is the corresponding score to the ROC AUC Curve. It is simply computed by measuring the Area Under the Curve (AUC). Maybe knowing the numerical score of the ROC AUC Curve will help us understand the lack of a blue line present in the plot.

In [48]:
r_a_score = roc_auc_score(Y_train, y_scores)
print("ROC AUC-Score:", r_a_score)

ROC AUC-Score: 0.9989979846470868

With a ROC AUC score of almost 100% (99.90%), I can see why there is barely a blue line present.

Summary¶

Analysis-Features Affecting Quality¶

When we explored the data, we noticed a weak negative correlation between quality and volatile_acidity. This means that the more volatile acidity present in the red wine, then there will be slight decrease in the percetion of quality. We also noticed a moderate positive correlation between quality and alcohol. This means the higher the ABV levels, there will be a moderate increase in the perception of quality. In fact, we can see how true the correlation is by looking at the feature importance of our best performing machine learning model, Random Forest.

In [49]:
importance = pd.DataFrame({'feature':X_train.columns,'importance':np.round(rand_forest.feature_importances_,3)})
importance = importance.sort_values('importance',ascending=False).set_index('feature')
importance.plot.bar()
Out[49]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x1d0274227b8>

Looking at the histogram above, we see that the two most important features on predicting quality is first volatile_acidity and then alcohol.

I can understand why a decrease in volatile acidity could affect quality. The more volatile acidity in wine, the more present the unpleasant vinegar taste you might find in some wine. This means less wouldn't give the unpleasant vinegar taste. I kind of understand the the positive correlation between alcohol and quality because some people like to drink alcoholic beverages with more alcohol present. However, this one may be one of the more subjective features because this mainly boils down to individual's preference.

Analysis-Features Dropped¶

I want to take a moment to look back at the features we dropped while optimizing our model: residual_sugar, free_sulfur_dioxide, total_sulfur_dioxide, and pH. These were 4 out of 5 features we could actually categorize properly (5th being alcohol.) Looking back at the pairplots and heatmap, these 4 features did not really have any correlation with quality to begin with.

I was surprised these features were dropped due to my initial beliefs regarding their effect on quality. For residual sugar, I thought people would care if wine was dry or sweet. For free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide, I learned the importance of properly the exact amount of free sulfur dioxide needed based on the levels of pH present. I categorized the feature depending on whether the wine followed these exact rules. For pH, I was surprised because I thought how acidic or basic the wine was would potentially affect the perception of quality. However, this one is not as bad to omit because there are three other features that affect the acidic levels that arguably do a better job at telling the story.

Conclusion¶

In conclusion, it seems the amount of (or lack of) vinegar taste and ABV levels have the most effect on perception of quality for red wine. My model did a good job of correctly classifying the bad quality wines while only being able to correctly classify a little over half of the good quality wines. However, I would like to point out the fact that the data set mainly contained "normal" wines (or wines with scores of 5-6.) This meant the data set mainly contained bad quality wines. Also, the lack of data could have had an effect on feature importance because it could have been an overwhelming dominance of one category which would have the model deem these features unnecessary and drop them. This is something to look into moving forward.
